Here's a typical setup:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // HttpClient: singleton so connections are reused (avoids socket exhaustion)
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<HttpClient>();

        // DataService: singleton because it wraps HttpClient and holds no
        // per-user/per-page state — one instance serves the whole app
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels: transient so each navigation gets fresh state
        // (no stale data when revisiting a page)
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages: transient to pair 1:1 with their ViewModel instance
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes?**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `HttpClient` | **Singleton** | Reuses TCP connections; creating one per request causes socket exhaustion. |
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Stateless wrapper over `HttpClient` — safe to share, avoids redundant allocations. |
| ViewModels | **Transient** | Each navigation should start with clean state. Singleton VMs would show stale data when you revisit a page. |
| Pages | **Transient** | Each page instance binds to its own VM. Matches the transient VM lifetime so they're created and discarded together. |

**When would you choose differently?**

- Use **Scoped** if you had a "session"-like boundary (rare in MAUI, common in Blazor/ASP.NET).
- Use **Singleton** for a VM only if it holds app-wide state you *want* to survive navigation (e.g., a settings VM).
- In production, replace the raw `HttpClient` singleton with `AddHttpClient<IDataService, DataService>()` from `Microsoft.Extensions.Http` to get pooled handler management.
